I'm truly surprised the Pound is as strong as it is, but traders...are traders by heart....so April 2019 is still far off. But to take off some of the recent profit run at end of year might be a nice way to gild the year and have a cush for what's in store for 2018. December 29 is last trading day of 2017. The pound hasn't be over 1.35 since September 21st and hasn't been under 1.30 since September 4th. So I think the pound stays in that range and possibly easing lower given the continued weakness of the British economy. The big event is the December EU summit that is going to decide whether to open trade talks or not and I don't think the UK has made enough progress for that to happen so I think the pound probably goes lower rather than higher.

The forward exchange rate, S(t,T), is found by synthetically replicating the future cash flows as follows: - Borrow P(t,T) pounds sterling today (time t) where P(t,T) is the discount function from T to t; repay 1 pound sterling at time T - Exchange P(t,T) pounds sterling today at the spot market exchange rate, S(t), for S(t) P(t,T) dollars - Invest S(t) P(t,T) dollars sterling; get S(t) P(t, T) / Q(t,T) dollars back at time T So the forward exchange rate is S(t,T) = S(t) P(t, T) / Q(t,T). Back of the envelope estimate USD 2 mo LIBOR ~ 1.3%, BGP LIBOR ~ 0.5% and spot USD/GBP ~ 1.31, the the forward exchange rate is about 1.32. (Reality check for past month and a half, GBP has been trading in the 1.30 to 1.32 range.)
